For this, we first create a temporary array x of size 43 filled with zeros. This is because there are 43 labels to classify the data into. Then we run a loop for each label where we compare all labels to every label number and add count to the label number if they match. While this is computationally intensive, it is a simple and straightforward approach. Below is the code:

```python
x=np.zeros(43)
for i in range(0, 43):
    for number in range(len(y_train)):
        if y_train[number]==i:
            x[i]+=1
```

####3. Describe, and identify where in your code, what your final model architecture looks like including model type, layers, layer sizes, connectivity, etc.) Consider including a diagram and/or table describing the final model.

The code for my final model is located in the 8th cell of the ipython notebook. For the architecture, I did experimentation with a modified LeNet architecture. Below is an table showing the architecture:



|      Layer      |               Description                |
| :-------------: | :--------------------------------------: |
|      Input      |         32x32x1 Grayscale image          |
| Convolution 7x7 | 2x2 stride, valid padding, outputs 13x13x4 |
|      RELU       |  applied on previous convolution layer   |
| Convolution 4x4 | 1x1 stride, valid padding, outputs 10x10x8 |
|      RELU       |  applied on previous convolution layer   |
|     Flatten     |         converts 10x10x8 to 800          |
| Fully connected |         input is 800, outputs 43         |



In this model, images are loaded as (32, 32, 1) array which are entered into a convolutional layer with a filter size of (7, 7), depth of 4 and a stride of (2, 2). This results in the output image of (13, 13, 4), which is passed through RELU activation for continuous output. This is then fed into another convolutional layer with a filter size of (4, 4), depth of 8 and a stride of (1, 1). Finally, the output image is (10, 10, 8) and is passed through RELU activation and then flattened to 800 neurons. Finally these 800 neurons reduce to 43 outputs in the final layer.



####4. Describe how, and identify where in your code, you trained your model. The discussion can include the type of optimizer, the batch size, number of epochs and any hyperparameters such as learning rate.

The code for training the model is located in the 9th cell of the ipython notebook. Following were the parameters experimented with:

Batch size: I tried batch sizes of 64, 128, 256, 512 and 2048. Amongst all the choices, there was minimal difference in the result. Hence I chose 256 to reduce time consumed in training.

Learning rate: By experimenting with learning rate, it seemed 0.005 was too high to even train the model. The rate of 0.0001 was too slow to converge. The rates 0.002 and 0.0005 did not create better results than 0.001 and 0.0015. Selecting between the 2 values, 0.00125, also did not produce better results. Reducing the rate to 0.0008 also did not produce better result, so it was increased to 0.0009 which, in fact, did generate better results. While I think these small changes should not affect a model too much, better results are certainly good to have.

Number of epochs: With Epochs at 10, the model starts to stabilize at around 90% accuracy. By increasing epochs to 50, I looked for increase in accuracy in the model, but there was no such observation. So, I reduced it to 25 for a stable output.

Optimizer: Currently, I'm using the adaptive moment estimation (Adam) based optimizer which calculates the adaptive learning rate of each parameter. I didn't experiment with other optimizers since that would require much time to fully understand and I intend to do so after this submission. 



####5. Describe the approach taken for finding a solution. Include in the discussion the results on the training, validation and test sets and where in the code these were calculated. Your approach may have been an iterative process, in which case, outline the steps you took to get to the final solution and why you chose those steps. Perhaps your solution involved an already well known implementation or architecture. In this case, discuss why you think the architecture is suitable for the current problem.

Note: Most of the decisions below were based on getting better validation accuracy. While training can be random and, therefore results can be inconsistent, but with multiple iterations, the answer is more likely to be correct than not.

For this project, I used a 3-stage approach to build the above listed network:

First, I built a network similar to the original LeNet implementation for MNIST, i.e. 

C > MP > C > MP > F > FC > FC 

where C is Convolutional layer, MP is Max Pooling, F is Flatten and FC is Fully Connected layer. Note that each convolutional or fully connected layer a RELU activation at the end (except the last layer). The observed validation accuracy here was about 85%. I chose this architecture because LeNet is simple yet powerful architecture that performed very well in classifying the written images. The traffic signs like, words, are based on shapes more than colors. While advanced networks that deploy colors can certainly do much better (for example, a blue something sign definitely won't be a mistaken as a red stop sign), classification based on shape only can also be pretty accurate.

One thing to note here is that using convolution layer here makes sense since traffic signs contain internal patterns. For example, pattern of curve in S of STOP in a stop sign would be something that would be recognized in the first layer. The word S itself may be recognized in the second convolution layer within the network.

Second, to experiment with the architecture, I increased convolution layers to 3, decreased it to 1, removed first, then second and then both max pooling, increased fully connected layers to 3 and decreased it to 1. I tried several combinations of all of these things. While this took a long time, I could relate the experiments with the theory that layers capturing patterns and patterns become more complex as layers increase and that some data could be lost with max pooling, but it reduces the computational requirement in the network. Eventually, after testing various configurations, it seemed that a configuration with 3 convoluted, 1 pooling and 3 fully connected layers had similar accuracy as 2 convoluted and 1 fully connected layer, suggesting some of the layers were not being fully utilized. The model is as shown below:

C > C > F > FC

Note that each convolutional layer a RELU activation at the end. My target was to avoid under-fit (accuracy below 90%) as well as avoid over-fit (excess training in large network) and to train the network quickly (since I'm doing CPU-based training). By experimenting with all these layers and observing the validation accuracy and time to train, I finally selected the architecture with 2 convolution layers and 1 fully connected layer, which still had validation accuracy of about 85% before optimization. 

Third, after deciding the architecture, I started experimenting with filter sizes. As per theory, the initial layers of the network capture patterns that combine up in top layers to form features in an image. The first pattern would be the edges: some traffic signs are circular, some are triangular while some are rectangular or diamond-shaped. The text within them is large too, with large edges again. These are large patterns and for their recognition, a large filter can be used in the first convolution layer. Furthermore, even a 2x2 stride can be used here. So I experimented with 1x1, 2x2, 3x3, 5x5, 7x7 and 9x9 size filters and the best filter was 7x7. Similarly, for the 2nd convolution layer, 4x4 seemed to be the best filter amongst 1x1, 2x2, 3x3, 4x4 and 5x5. For the stride, 2x2 in the first layer gave better results than with max pooling, so the same was selected. Next, I experimented with depths of 1, 2, 4, 8 and 32 for the first convolution layer and selected 4. For the next convolution layer, I experimented with depths of 2, 4, 6, 8, 16 and 64 and selected 8.

The validation accuracy on this architecture was 91.7% after training for 25 epochs. The observed test accuracy was 90.7%. While I could reach validation accuracy of over 95% with larger architecture and running several epochs, the test accuracy still remained close to 90%. So the ideal case here would be where test and validation accuracy are close, implying normal-fit (or maybe a little under-fit). This is what is achieved in the above case. This suggests that the model can work consistently well even with different images.
